Send SMS with AT Commands | Towers of Power                                                      Towers of Power      An ITP class about how cellphone networks work in order to get your project to speak GSM!               Menu      Skip to content      Home   Syllabus   Hardware Materials   Readings & Resources   Labs & How-To      Intro to AT Commands    Send SMS with AT Commands    SMS to the Internet    Using OpenBTS       Projects   Archive                                                   Send SMS with AT Commands               Sending an SMS message is an operation which we will be spending a lot of time looking at because its provides that opportunity send small chunks of information anywhere on the network. Similarly, SMS messages allow us to send information to a device which is located on a network. Using SMS messages for remote sensing and remote control open a range of interaction possibilities and capabilities in our projects. SMS also has many advantages over GPRS which will be exploring.   So, what is an SMS? SMS stands for Short Messaging Service. This is a service which allows a maximum of 160 characters to be sent over a cellular network. Ha! Ok that’s the most important stuff we need to know. Check out the wiki article for more in-depth information. Now lets start sending messages!!!   To begin, follow the tutorial above to connect to the device. Once you are connected, we need to tell the module what type of text mode we are in. There are two modes, PDU (protocol description unit) and Text Mode. PDU mode is used to send hexadecimal-octets and semi decimal-octets which we’re not going to bother with. We want to send text! To put the module in text mode, we use the AT Command ‘+CMGF’. Since we are writing a parameter, the command format will look like this: AT+CMGF=1 . The number one signifies which mode we want(ie Text Mode). You should receive the response ‘OK’. You can verify which mode the module is in by performing a read command, AT+CMGF? , which should return ‘1’.   Now that we are in the correct mode, we can use the command ‘+CMGS’ to send a text message. This command takes several variables including the destination address (which is the phone number we want to send the message to), the address_type and the body of the text message. So what is address_type you ask? There are two values that are typically used for address_type:   129 – It means the value of address is formatted as either national number or anything else. Example addresses: “85291234567”, “91234567”.  145 – It means the value of address is formatted as an international number. Example address: “+85291234567″.  The module is set to ‘145’ by default.   So putting the command together looks like this:   AT+CMGS=”phone-number”, 129 <cr><body of message><ctl-z>   Wait, what is this <cr> and <ctl-z> business? <cr> stands for character return. This is needed so the module knows that the body of the message is to follow. In CoolTerm, run the command AT+CMGS=”1234567″, 129 and then hit Enter. Enter here will act as our character return and CoolTerm will now prompt you with ‘>’. This means you can now start typing the body of the message. Once you have completed typing the message NICK-DOES USING CTL-Z WORK WITH COOLTERM? NEED TO TEST THIS   Congratulations!!! You just sent a text message!   Explore AT Commands   Now explore a bit on your own. Start by trying to send an SMS from your phone to the GSM module. Read the message from the module and then delete. Then start using the module to explore the surrounding area and network status. Think about what we discussed in class and start exploring how your module is operating on the network.   Here is a cheat sheet of the most useful AT Commands:   AT – Check to see if the module is active. Should return ‘OK’   AT+CREG? – Is the module registered to the network? Set the mode first: AT+CREG=2   AT+COPS? – What network is the module registered?   AT+CMGF=1 – This puts the module into text mode so messages can be sent/received   AT+CMGS=”number”,129 <cr>< body of message> <1A> – Send a text message.   AT+CMGL=”ALL” – Lists all text messages that are on the device (or network)   AT+CMGR=<index> – Read SMS message at index number   AT+QBAND? – What band am I on?   AT+CIMI – Get the IMSI number from the module   AT+CSQ – Check the signal strength   AT+GSN – Get IMEI number   AT+QSPN – Get service provider name   AT+QCCID – Get CCID number from SIM   AT+CRSM – SIM card restricted access (still researching)   AT+CSIM – Generic SIM access (still researching)   and my personal favorite:   AT+QENG? – report the cell description of the main cell and six neighboring cells.   and a cool trick:   *#06# – shows your IMEI number on the phone                                                    Proudly powered by WordPress

Send SMS with AT Commands | Towers of Power                                                      Towers of Power      An ITP class about how cellphone networks work in order to get your project to speak GSM!               Menu      Skip to content      Home   Syllabus   Hardware Materials   Readings & Resources   Labs & How-To      Intro to AT Commands    Send SMS with AT Commands    SMS to the Internet    Using OpenBTS       Projects   Archive                                                   Send SMS with AT Commands               Sending an SMS message is an operation which we will be spending a lot of time looking at because its provides that opportunity send small chunks of information anywhere on the network. Similarly, SMS messages allow us to send information to a device which is located on a network. Using SMS messages for remote sensing and remote control open a range of interaction possibilities and capabilities in our projects. SMS also has many advantages over GPRS which will be exploring.   So, what is an SMS? SMS stands for Short Messaging Service. This is a service which allows a maximum of 160 characters to be sent over a cellular network. Ha! Ok that’s the most important stuff we need to know. Check out the wiki article for more in-depth information. Now lets start sending messages!!!   To begin, follow the tutorial above to connect to the device. Once you are connected, we need to tell the module what type of text mode we are in. There are two modes, PDU (protocol description unit) and Text Mode. PDU mode is used to send hexadecimal-octets and semi decimal-octets which we’re not going to bother with. We want to send text! To put the module in text mode, we use the AT Command ‘+CMGF’. Since we are writing a parameter, the command format will look like this: AT+CMGF=1 . The number one signifies which mode we want(ie Text Mode). You should receive the response ‘OK’. You can verify which mode the module is in by performing a read command, AT+CMGF? , which should return ‘1’.   Now that we are in the correct mode, we can use the command ‘+CMGS’ to send a text message. This command takes several variables including the destination address (which is the phone number we want to send the message to), the address_type and the body of the text message. So what is address_type you ask? There are two values that are typically used for address_type:   129 – It means the value of address is formatted as either national number or anything else. Example addresses: “85291234567”, “91234567”.  145 – It means the value of address is formatted as an international number. Example address: “+85291234567″.  The module is set to ‘145’ by default.   So putting the command together looks like this:   AT+CMGS=”phone-number”, 129 <cr><body of message><ctl-z>   Wait, what is this <cr> and <ctl-z> business? <cr> stands for character return. This is needed so the module knows that the body of the message is to follow. In CoolTerm, run the command AT+CMGS=”1234567″, 129 and then hit Enter. Enter here will act as our character return and CoolTerm will now prompt you with ‘>’. This means you can now start typing the body of the message. Once you have completed typing the message NICK-DOES USING CTL-Z WORK WITH COOLTERM? NEED TO TEST THIS   Congratulations!!! You just sent a text message!   Explore AT Commands   Now explore a bit on your own. Start by trying to send an SMS from your phone to the GSM module. Read the message from the module and then delete. Then start using the module to explore the surrounding area and network status. Think about what we discussed in class and start exploring how your module is operating on the network.   Here is a cheat sheet of the most useful AT Commands:   AT – Check to see if the module is active. Should return ‘OK’   AT+CREG? – Is the module registered to the network? Set the mode first: AT+CREG=2   AT+COPS? – What network is the module registered?   AT+CMGF=1 – This puts the module into text mode so messages can be sent/received   AT+CMGS=”number”,129 <cr>< body of message> <1A> – Send a text message.   AT+CMGL=”ALL” – Lists all text messages that are on the device (or network)   AT+CMGR=<index> – Read SMS message at index number   AT+QBAND? – What band am I on?   AT+CIMI – Get the IMSI number from the module   AT+CSQ – Check the signal strength   AT+GSN – Get IMEI number   AT+QSPN – Get service provider name   AT+QCCID – Get CCID number from SIM   AT+CRSM – SIM card restricted access (still researching)   AT+CSIM – Generic SIM access (still researching)   and my personal favorite:   AT+QENG? – report the cell description of the main cell and six neighboring cells.   and a cool trick:   *#06# – shows your IMEI number on the phone                                                    Proudly powered by WordPress
